Write the equation of the following graph given that the points \((1, 4)\) and \((2,10)\) lie on the curve.

generalfeedback.text: In this case notice that the y-intercept is \(2\). The graph tends to the horizontal line \(y = 1\), so \(1\) is the constant term. Thus the equation of the curve is of the from \(c \cdot a^x +1\). We are given that the points \((1, 4)\) and \((2,10)\) lie on the curve. Thus we have, \[ c \cdot a^1 +1 = 4 \qquad \mbox{ and } \qquad c \cdot a^2 +1 = 10, \] that is, \[ c \cdot a^1 = 3 \qquad \mbox{ and } \qquad c \cdot a^2 = 9. \] Notice that these equations are satisfied if \(c = 1\) and \(a = 3\). Therefore the equation of the curve is {@ta1@}
